rComments: misleading prof

Her multiple choice will trick you every time, many people in the class would have 90s on the short answer and be in the 50s or 60s on mc. She seems very nice in lecture but when approached or attempted to reach outside of class she is stubborn on her ways.

Sometimes she can act sassy and have attitude, but she's actually nice and not too bad of a prof. She references the real world a lot which makes me enjoy the class. Her lecture slides are amazing. Super nice prof, and decent lecturer in combination with the MindTap assignments. She curves with the test short answer though, so you can give a right answer and lose most marks on the question if it's not absolutely perfect.

She is wonderful!

she is unfair, the 2 hour midterm was actually 2 hours, of full on writing. She doesnt care about students. She is so unorganized in her lectures and I am a fourth year taking this 2nd year course. IT IS HORRIBLE, UGHHHHH!

rComments: I had a great semester with Dr. Metz. She makes statistics approachable and is very accessible if you have any questions. As a student who is bad at math and scared of it, she makes it less daunting and the first test is almost all theory based. Can do well by just attending lecture and doing problem sets.

*Instead of writing 2-3 papers throughout the semester, you get assignments usually small in size but large in number and "flavors". Beware: you MAY or MAY NOT like that. *Tests are fair and clear. I'd say textbook and lectures are 50/50. *Actually a good person. *That said, her class discussions are often ideological echo chambers, sadly.

Molly Metz is able to plan her courses in the student's shoes and executes them in the student's best interest. The way she organizes her content, explains & cautions us on harder content, engages the class, makes a confusing course become much less confusing. To succeed, simply listen: her lectures are very engaging anyways!

She gives great lectures and makes difficult concepts clear. However, this course gave heavy workload and makes you suffer. I took her class in the summer term, and she placed 3 heavy chapters in one week, making 3 problems sets due in five days along with an essay. I had to sacrifice my sleep time merely trying to follow.

She seems nice and lectures were easy to follow, textbook really helped too. But the midterm mark scheme is very unclear and ambiguous. Assignment and exam grades were released at the same time when final grades were out so students weren't able to challenge the assignment grading. Note: assignment was due late march, final grades released mid may.

Purposefully omits questions on midterm and final to lower the average instead of curving down. Also marks assignments extremely strictly instead of laying down straight forward instructions to set students up for success. One of those profs that loves adjusting marks instead of designing proper questions and assesments.
Dr. Metz is a super awesome Prof. Extremely approachable and is amazing at explaining statistical concepts and makes it super fun!

Intentionally makes her exams so that the averages will be low. People like her because she has this faux-nice facade but anyone with any sense can see right through it. If she was actually nice she wouldn't refuse to take questions right before exams and instruct her TAs to do the same. She's actually quite rude.

Take her courses if you are genuinely interested in learning and pushing yourself to really understand the topic. She is tough but fair. Her assignments require you to actually apply what you have learned and think deeply rather then repeat. Very sweet and really cares about students!

Actually cares about students. People who complained about the midterms were those who did not bother understanding the big picture of what we were learning (for PSY331; admittedly, the first midterm didn't go well for me at all but the second was much better), or didn't bother reading the textbook (PSY202). Lots of chances to boost your mark.

She took a really interesting topic and made it a lot more difficult than it needed to be. Textbook readings, weekly article readings with 500 word article response papers, proposals, essay rough draft, essay peer edits, final essay, application brief, and two midterm exams. Overkill on everything. Plus, the marking was very tough.
